	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />NSF has 4 KB bankswitching. You'd need something fast for this, and that means a CPLD or FPGA.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Memblers</b> [ Fri Jan 13, 2006 2:52 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />It'd be like building any other 6502 computer.  Except sound is in the CPU.  Check out the various projects on 6502.org if you want to see some stuff people have made.
<br />
<br />A PIC can't replace an FPGA, but you could use some discrete logic parts.  You'll need address decoding especially.  NSF bankswitching is possible with discrete parts too, but you could get by without any bankswitching to play most stuff.  (I have a ton that I manually 'unbankswitched' for my SNES NSF player.. lots of them use it simply to optimize the NSF filesize)

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
